{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 7, "page_label": "8"}, "page_content": "8\nAutism in adolescents\nTeenage years can be a difficult time for both the adolescent and \ntheir parents. Teenage years can be particularly challenging for \nautistic people.\nTo support parents with older children \nwho are at the identification stage. Walking \nthem through the basics in an accessible \nmanner, addressing key challenges, including \nco-occurring conditions, puberty, and \nsafeguarding, as well as looking to the future. \nAdvising on schooling options and beyond. \nThis is a guide with a focus on difference - not \ndeficit.\nLate diagnosis\n\u2022 While many autistic children are diagnosed in early childhood,  \nsome are diagnosed later in life.\n\u2022 It might not be until they\u2019re at primary school or secondary school (or even \nadulthood) that the question of autism comes up.\n\u2022 During the adolescent years, social and behavioural differences can become more \nobvious.\n\u2022 The diagnosis itself won\u2019t change your child, or the way that you think or feel", "type": "Document"}}